This paper is likely to belong to the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it deals with training lexicalized parsers using bilingual corpora. It also involves the use of Universal Dependency Treebanks, which are commonly used in natural language processing research. 

The paper also involves the use of machine learning techniques such as MaltParser and MaltOptimizer, which are commonly used in the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG). 

The approach presented in the paper involves training parsers that can analyze sentences in either of the learned languages, which involves the use of artificial intelligence techniques such as neural networks. This makes the paper likely to belong to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI). 

The paper also involves the use of optimization techniques to improve the accuracy of the parsers, which makes it likely to belong to the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). 

Finally, the paper mentions the use of the approach on texts with code-switching and when more languages are added, which makes it likely to belong to the sub-category of Computational and Data Linguistics (cs.CY).
